    <section id="volcano-experiment">
        <div class="experiment-content">
            <h2>Experiment 1: Create Your Own Erupting Volcano!</h2>
            
            <p>Have you ever wondered how a volcano erupts? Now, you can create one at home using simple materials you probably already have in your kitchen! This fun and easy experiment will not only amaze you but also teach you some cool science.</p>
            
            <h3>What You’re Making</h3>
            <p>We’re going to build a volcano and make it erupt using a fizzy reaction between baking soda and vinegar. The bubbly "lava" looks just like a real volcanic explosion (but don’t worry, it’s completely safe).</p>
            
            <h3>What You Need</h3>
            <ul>
            <li><strong>Baking Soda:</strong> About 2–3 spoonfuls.</li>
            <li><strong>Vinegar:</strong> Half a cup will do.</li>
            <li><strong>Dish Soap:</strong> Just a few drops to make extra bubbly lava.</li>
            <li><strong>Food Coloring:</strong> Red and yellow make your lava look fiery!</li>
            <li><strong>Plastic Bottle:</strong> To serve as the volcano's crater.</li>
            <li><strong>Clay or Papier-Mâché:</strong> To build the volcano structure.</li>
            <li><strong>Tray:</strong> To catch the mess from the eruption.</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Procedure</h3>
            <ol>
            <li>
                <strong>Build Your Volcano:</strong>
                <ul>
                <li>Use clay, papier-mâché, or play dough to shape a volcano around a plastic bottle or cup.</li>
                <li>Leave the top of the bottle open to act as the crater.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Get Your Volcano Ready for Action:</strong>
                <ul>
                <li>Place the volcano on a tray (trust us, it gets messy).</li>
                <li>Add 2–3 spoonfuls of baking soda inside the bottle.</li>
                <li>Drop a few drops of dish soap for extra foam.</li>
                <li>Add red and yellow food coloring for fiery lava.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Time to Erupt!</strong>
                <ul>
                <li>Pour in half a cup of vinegar and step back.</li>
                <li>Watch your volcano erupt with bubbly, colorful "lava"!</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            </ol>
            
            <h3>What’s Happening?</h3>
            <p>Here’s the science part:</p>
            <ul>
            <li>Baking soda (a base) reacts with vinegar (an acid) to produce carbon dioxide gas.</li>
            <li>The gas bubbles push the liquid up and out, simulating a volcanic eruption.</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Extra Fun Ideas</h3>
            <ul>
            <li>Experiment with different amounts of vinegar to change the eruption intensity.</li>
            <li>Research real volcanoes and compare them with your model.</li>
            <li>Try testing different "lava recipes" to see what works best.</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Quick Tips</h3>
            <ul>
            <li>Perform this experiment outside or on a tray for easier cleanup.</li>
            <li>Ask an adult for help if needed.</li>
            </ul>
            
            <p><strong>Why It’s Awesome:</strong> This experiment is fun, educational, and a great way to learn about chemical reactions. Perfect for school projects or just for fun!</p>
        </div>
        <img src="images/vol1.jpeg" alt="Volcano Eruption Experiment" class="experiment-image" width="300px">
      </section>
      

    </section>


    <section id="lemon-battery">
        <h2>Experiment 2: Lemon Battery Experiment</h2>
        <h3>Make Electricity with Lemons!</h3>
        
        <p>Did you know you can use lemons to create electricity? In this fun experiment, you’ll learn how to turn ordinary lemons into tiny batteries that can power a small device, like an LED light or a digital clock.</p>
        
        <h3>What You’ll Do</h3>
        <p>You’re going to use the acidic juice inside lemons to create a simple electrical circuit. The reaction between copper, zinc, and lemon juice generates electricity. This will help you understand how real batteries work!</p>
        
        <h3>What You’ll Need</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Lemons:</strong> 2–3 fresh ones (the juicier, the better).</li>
          <li><strong>Copper coins or strips:</strong> These act as the positive terminal of the battery.</li>
          <li><strong>Zinc nails or screws:</strong> These are the negative terminal.</li>
          <li><strong>Wires or alligator clips:</strong> To connect the lemons together.</li>
          <li><strong>A small LED light or clock:</strong> To show the battery in action.</li>
          <li><strong>A knife or scissors:</strong> To make small cuts in the lemons (get an adult’s help).</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h3>Steps to Follow</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Prepare Your Lemons:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Roll the lemons on a table to release their juice inside.</li>
              <li>Make two small cuts in each lemon—one for the copper piece and one for the zinc nail.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Set Up Your Electrodes:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Insert a copper coin or strip into one cut and a zinc nail into the other.</li>
              <li>Ensure they don’t touch inside the lemon.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Connect the Lemons:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Use wires or alligator clips to link the zinc nail in one lemon to the copper in the next.</li>
              <li>This creates a chain of lemons.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Power Something Small:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Attach the free zinc nail and copper strip at the ends of your lemon chain to an LED light or clock.</li>
              <li>Watch as your lemon battery brings it to life!</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ol>
        
        <h3>What’s Happening?</h3>
        <p>Here’s the science behind it:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Lemons have citric acid, which acts like a liquid that helps electricity flow (called an electrolyte).</li>
          <li>The zinc reacts with the acid and releases electrons (tiny particles that create electricity).</li>
          <li>The copper collects these electrons, and when they flow through the wires, they create electricity to power your device.</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h3>Try These Fun Variations</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Test other fruits or vegetables (like potatoes or oranges) to see if they work as batteries.</li>
          <li>Add more lemons to your chain and see if you can power a bigger device.</li>
          <li>Use a multimeter to measure how much voltage your battery generates.</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h3>Tips for Success</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Make sure the copper and zinc don’t touch inside the lemon—it won’t work if they do.</li>
          <li>Fresh, juicy lemons produce more electricity.</li>
          <li>Be careful when using sharp objects and ask an adult for help.</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h3>Why It’s Cool</h3>
        <p>This experiment is a simple way to understand how electricity and batteries work. Plus, it’s an exciting project to show off at school or to friends and family. Who knew lemons could do so much?</p>
        
        <p>Give it a try and see the power of citrus for yourself!</p>
      </section>

      <section id="density-tower-experiment">
        <div class="experiment-content">
          <h2>Experiment 3: Density Tower</h2>
          <h3>Build a Tower of Liquids!</h3>
          <p>Ever wondered why some objects float while others sink? In this experiment, you’ll create a colorful tower using different liquids like honey, water, and oil. Each liquid has a different density, which allows them to stack in layers. You’ll also test how objects float or sink depending on their density.</p>
      
          <h3>What You’ll Need</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Clear glass or container:</strong> To see the layers clearly.</li>
            <li><strong>Honey or syrup:</strong> The densest layer.</li>
            <li><strong>Water:</strong> Add food coloring for fun!</li>
            <li><strong>Cooking oil:</strong> A lighter liquid for the upper layer.</li>
            <li><strong>Optional liquids:</strong> Rubbing alcohol, milk, or dish soap for more layers.</li>
            <li><strong>Small objects:</strong> Examples include a coin, grape, ping-pong ball, paperclip, and bead.</li>
            <li><strong>Spoon or pipette:</strong> To carefully add the liquids.</li>
          </ul>
      
          <h3>Steps to Follow</h3>
          <ol>
            <li><strong>Prepare Your Liquids:</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Pour each liquid into a separate cup. You can add food coloring to water or rubbing alcohol to make them colorful and easy to identify.</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Layer the Liquids:</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Start by pouring the heaviest liquid (honey or syrup) into the container.</li>
                <li>Slowly and gently add the next liquid (like colored water) by pouring it over the back of a spoon.</li>
                <li>Continue adding layers with lighter liquids, like oil, until your tower is complete.</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Test Object Buoyancy:</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Drop small objects into the density tower one at a time. Watch where they settle in the layers and take note of their position.</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ol>
      
          <h3>What’s Happening?</h3>
          <p>Here’s the science behind it:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Density</strong> refers to how much “stuff” is packed into a space. Heavier liquids like honey have more density and sink to the bottom, while lighter liquids like oil stay on top.</li>
            <li>Objects float or sink based on their density compared to the liquid they are in. A ping-pong ball floats on oil but sinks in water, while a coin sinks to the bottom.</li>
          </ul>
      
          <h3>Try These Fun Variations</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Add more liquids, like dish soap or rubbing alcohol, to create more layers.</li>
            <li>Predict where each object will settle before dropping it in.</li>
            <li>Stir the liquids gently and watch them slowly separate back into layers over time.</li>
          </ul>
      
          <h3>Tips for Success</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Pour liquids slowly to avoid mixing them. Using the back of a spoon helps control the flow.</li>
            <li>Use clear containers for the best visual effect.</li>
            <li>Clean up spills immediately to avoid sticky messes.</li>
          </ul>
      
          <h3>Why It’s Cool</h3>
          <p>This experiment is a fantastic way to explore the concept of density. It’s colorful, easy to set up, and helps you understand why some objects float while others sink. Plus, it’s a great science fair project that’s sure to grab attention!</p>
        </div>
        <img src="images/density-tower.jpeg" alt="Density Tower Experiment" class="experiment-image" width="300px">
      </section>

      <section id="electromagnet-test">
        <div class="experiment-content">
          <h2>Experiment 4: Electromagnet Strength Test</h2>
          <h3>Explore Magnetic Power!</h3>
          <p>Have you ever wondered how magnets can be made with electricity? In this experiment, you’ll create an electromagnet using a nail, wire, and battery. By changing the number of wire coils around the nail, you’ll test how it affects the magnet’s strength.</p>
          <h3>What You’ll Do</h3>
          <p>Build a simple electromagnet and test how its strength changes based on the number of wire coils wrapped around the nail. This will give you insight into the relationship between electricity and magnetism.</p>
          <h3>What You’ll Need</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Iron nail (3–4 inches long)</li>
            <li>Insulated copper wire (3–4 feet long)</li>
            <li>Battery (D-cell or 9V)</li>
            <li>Paper clips or small metal objects</li>
            <li>Electrical tape</li>
          </ul>
          <h3>Steps to Follow</h3>
          <ol>
            <li><strong>Wrap the Wire Around the Nail:</strong> Coil the wire tightly around the nail, leaving 3 inches free on each end.</li>
            <li><strong>Connect to the Battery:</strong> Strip insulation from the wire ends and attach them to the battery terminals.</li>
            <li><strong>Test Your Electromagnet:</strong> Use the magnet to pick up paper clips or metal objects.</li>
            <li><strong>Experiment with More Coils:</strong> Add more coils and observe changes in magnetic strength.</li>
          </ol>
          <h3>What’s Happening?</h3>
          <p>Electricity flowing through the wire creates a magnetic field, turning the nail into an electromagnet. More coils increase the magnetic field's concentration and strength.</p>
          <h3>Try These Fun Variations</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Test different battery voltages.</li>
            <li>Use nails of different sizes.</li>
            <li>Measure magnet strength with a spring scale.</li>
          </ul>
          <h3>Tips for Success</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Use fresh batteries for better results.</li>
            <li>Ensure coils are tightly wrapped.</li>
            <li>Disconnect the battery when not in use.</li>
          </ul>
          <p><strong>Why It’s Cool:</strong> Learn how electricity creates magnetic fields, a principle used in many modern technologies!</p>
        </div>
      </section>
       
